name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: If Tesla repeats the same return over the next year the market cap would be $6.3 trillion. Two years of repeat performance and the cap becomes $52 trillion. Of course, that‚Äôs 70% larger than the entire S&P 500, but by then any short seller is long bankrupt. 58/58 END

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: A 90% decline takes the cap to $66B, 2.2x current run rate revenues & 37x a hypothetical 6% net margin. A mere 80% drop gets to a $132B cap, 4.4x revenues, and to give the bulls on Tesla not being a car company credit, still 37x a 12% hypothetical profit margin. Ridiculous. 54/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: At 1.75% of the index, a decline of 80-90% would be heavy, but realistic. Impossible to decline that much? An 88% drop takes you all the way back to‚Ä¶.where Tesla‚Äôs shares began the year. 53/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: We‚Äôll see what happens after Monday, when Tesla assumes the #6 perch in the index. When the argument for passive is low fees, remind me in ten years how much of the loss in Tesla‚Äôs shares from here should be considered a ‚Äúfee,‚Äù or a tax on stupidity. 52/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: The realistic case: The performance of the stock from here is a giant loss over time and the Tesla cult loses interest in the brand. In fact, they come to hate the brand because of their coming stock losses, customer and employee mistreatment. 47/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: The best case for shareholders: If Tesla grows the aforementioned sales for the next decade by 28% to $335B (it won‚Äôt), the stock will trade for no more than 1x sales, because it‚Äôs a CAR company. 45/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: Auto manufacturers trade for less than sales because they make ~3% net margins and earn that same ~3% on capital and revenues grow at ~3%. We can call the industry 3x3x3 (new material here folks). The car business is a bad business, and that‚Äôs what Tesla is trying to disrupt? 44/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: Total capital raised is now $40B before retained losses. What does Tesla earn on capital? Nothing yet. Equity is less than capital raised from stock sales by the amount of cumulative losses. Per share book is of course higher thanks to successful stock sales way above book...40/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: So far in 2020, Tesla has borrowed an additional net $200m and sold $12.3B of new shares (assuming a sale of the most recent $5B ‚Äúat-the-market‚Äù). Bulls revere the cash on the balance sheet, but it didn‚Äôt come from profit or free cash. 39/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: Through the end of 2019 Tesla had sold $12.7B in shares and borrowed $16B in debt and preferred stock. Total capital raised of $28B exceeded FY 2019 revenues of $25B and produced a $6B cumulative LOSS. 38/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: The best course of action for Tesla is to keep selling ‚Äúat-the-market‚Äù blocks, with no prospectus, road show or risk warning, to the dumb money that is willing, or compelled, as is the passive crowd, to pay dangerous prices. The dilution at today‚Äôs prices is infinitesimal. 37/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: At ‚Äúonly‚Äù 10% per year, the fully diluted market cap grows to $2 trillion, almost where $AAPL is valued these days. At a 10% shareholder return, to trade at 30x earnings, Tesla will need to be earning $67 billion. 32/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: What prospective return does the Tesla bull expect, or the passive investor with 1.75% of capital in the shares come Monday? At 15% a year, the market cap, assuming no further dilution, grows to $3T over the next decade, ~10% of the market value of the entire S&P 500 today. 31/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: 80% of Tesla‚Äôs shares float, not owned by insiders, which means the adjusted market cap weight will be $528B, compelling somewhere between $50 and $75B of direct index purchases, not to mention those needed by index huggers and closet indexers. 29/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: 25x sales? 2,030x GAAP earnings? 422x earnings assuming Toyota‚Äôs best in industry 6% profit margin? Heck, even 85 times Microsoft‚Äôs 30% profit margin (a bone for the Tesla is not a car company but also a software/robotaxi crowd). Welcome to the game, index fund investors. 28/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: The gain matches the percentage rise seen by Yahoo during the week between its announcement & addition. The $279B gain is LARGER than the $215B market cap of the world‚Äôs largest auto manufacturer, Toyota. Tesla‚Äôs $659B cap is on 948M shares out at 9/30 (up 5% since YE 2019). 25/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: On November 16, the S&P index committee announced Tesla would be added on December 21. The market cap was $380B. Here on Saturday December 19, the stock price at $695 yields a market cap of $659B ($BRK, the current #6 is $528B) up $279B or 73% since the announcement. 24/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: Tesla had cut R&D & SG&A, drew on reserves and leaned on environmental carbon credits to ‚Äúearn‚Äù a GAAP profit for a necessary four quarters. They did so for five. Oddly, revenues only grew 15% in 2019, prior to the pandemic, in part for a reduction in customer tax incentives. 22/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: Never has the S&P 500 committee brought in a company so large by market cap as will be the case with Tesla's inclusion. Nor have they ever brought in a company at so high a spot in the cap-weighted index, at #6, one notch ahead of Berkshire Hathaway. Insanity. 20/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: Pull up the long-term charts to see how these ‚Äútimely‚Äù additions fared post admittance. The most prominent additions in 1999 were America Online (discussed in my 12/5 thread) and Yahoo, whose mania also reminds me of Tesla... 5/

name: Christopher Bloomstran
tweet: Let‚Äôs get ready to tumble! Come Monday, $TSLA enters the S&P 500, as the world is aware. This is the one you will tell your grandkids about, or at least the new crop of investors, wondering what the bubble of 2020 was like. Tesla can be your example of the insanity....1/
